            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this simple loan calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool lets you model both
                <strong>true simple interest loans</strong> and
                <strong>standard amortized loans</strong> (like most personal
                loans, auto loans, and mortgages). You can switch between them
                using the tabs at the top of the calculator.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Simple interest formula</h3>
              <p>
                For a true simple interest loan, interest is charged only on the
                original principal.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Total interest (simple interest):</strong></p>
                <p>\( I = P \times r \times t \)</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( P \) = principal (loan amount)</li>
                  <li>
                    \( r \) = annual interest rate (decimal, e.g. 7.5% → 0.075)
                  </li>
                  <li>\( t \) = time in years</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Total paid:</strong> \( P + I \)</p>
                <p><strong>Average payment per period:</strong></p>
                <p>\( \text{Payment} = \dfrac{P + I}{n} \)</p>
                <p>
                  where \( n \) is the number of payments (e.g. years × 12 for
                  monthly payments).
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                In practice, some simple interest loans still use a fixed
                payment and allocate part of each payment to interest and the
                rest to principal. Our schedule shows this breakdown so you can
                see how much of each payment goes where.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Amortized loan formula</h3>
              <p>
                For standard amortized loans, interest is charged on the
                <em>remaining balance</em> each period. The payment is
                calculated so the loan is fully paid off at the end of the term.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Periodic interest rate:</strong></p>
                <p>\( i = \dfrac{r}{m} \)</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( r \) = annual interest rate (decimal)</li>
                  <li>
                    \( m \) = number of payments per year (12 monthly, 26
                    bi-weekly, 52 weekly, 1 annual)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Number of payments:</strong> \( n = m \times t \)</p>
                <p><strong>Payment (amortized):</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Payment} = P \times \dfrac{i(1+i)^n}{(1+i)^n - 1} \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Each payment is split into interest and principal. Interest for
                a period is \( \text{Interest} = \text{Balance} \times i \), and
                principal is \( \text{Principal} = \text{Payment} -
                \text{Interest} \).
              </p>

              <h3>3. Extra payments and interest savings</h3>
              <p>
                When you enter an <strong>extra payment per period</strong>, the
                calculator:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Computes a base schedule with no extra payments.</li>
                <li>
                  Computes a second schedule with your extra payment applied
                  directly to principal.
                </li>
                <li>Shows how many payments and how much interest you save.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Extra payments are one of the most effective ways to reduce both
                the length and total cost of a loan.
              </p>

              <h2>How to use the simple loan calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>Enter your <strong>loan amount</strong> (principal).</li>
                <li>Enter the <strong>annual interest rate</strong>.</li>
                <li>Set the <strong>loan term</strong> in years or months.</li>
                <li>
                  Choose your <strong>payment frequency</strong> (monthly,
                  bi-weekly, weekly, or annual).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Optionally, add a fixed <strong>extra payment</strong> per
                  period.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Select <strong>Simple Interest</strong> or
                  <strong>Amortized (Standard)</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>Calculate</strong> to see your payment, totals,
                  and full schedule.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Simple interest vs amortized loans: which is better?</h2>
              <p>
                Neither method is always “better” — it depends on the rate,
                term, and how the lender structures the loan. However:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Simple interest loans</strong> are easier to
                  understand and can be cheaper if you pay off the loan early,
                  because interest is based on time and original principal.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Amortized loans</strong> are standard for mortgages
                  and many personal loans. Payments are fixed, and interest
                  naturally declines as you pay down the balance.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use this calculator to compare both methods side by side with
                the same principal, rate, and term.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>
                Is this calculator suitable for personal loans and auto loans?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Most personal and auto loans are amortized with fixed
                payments, which is exactly what the “Amortized (Standard)” mode
                models. If your lender advertises a “simple interest” loan, you
                can switch to the Simple Interest tab and enable the “true
                simple interest” toggle.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for interest-only loans?</h3>
              <p>
                This calculator assumes you are paying down principal over time.
                For pure interest-only periods, you can approximate by:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Setting a short term for the interest-only phase and using the
                  payment equal to interest only.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Then modeling a second loan for the remaining balance and
                  term.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>What happens if I change payment frequency?</h3>
              <p>The calculator automatically adjusts:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>The number of payments per year.</li>
                <li>The effective interest rate per period.</li>
                <li>
                  The schedule dates (assuming payments start one period from
                  today).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This lets you compare, for example, monthly vs bi-weekly
                payments on the same loan.
              </p>

              <h3>Is this financial advice?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This calculator is for educational and planning purposes
                only. Actual loan terms, fees, and interest calculations vary by
                lender and jurisdiction. Always review your loan agreement and,
                if needed, consult a qualified financial professional.
              </p>
            </section>
